Cherry Blossom 10-Mile Race Report

Akshata Jha, Breanna Neuwirth, and Andrin Zuellig

December 13, 2024

Introduction

The primary question in this consulting project is: How does age influence athletic performance in the Cherry Blossom 10-Mile Race? The goal is to provide a clear and simple answer to understand how age and other factors impact race performance. With the help of our client we were able to scrape around 400,000 observations from the Race Data website into a dataframe which then gave us a lot of data to analyze for trends.

Background

The Cherry Blossom 10-Mile Race began as a small local event in Washington, D.C., designed to bring the community together for a fun and challenging experience. Over time, it has grown into a renowned annual event, attracting thousands of runners from across the country and around the world. Its rich history, spanning five decades, provides us a dataset with thousands of entries to explore long-term trends in athletic performance. Age plays a notable role in endurance races, with performance generally peaking in early adulthood and gradually decreasing with age. This project seeks to analyze how age affects race performance and identify key trends over time.

Data

The dataset for this project contains over 400,000 race observations spanning more than 50 years of the Cherry Blossom 10-Mile Race. It includes detailed participant-level data with the following variables:

Name: Name of the participant. PiD_TiD: Rank within their division. PiS_TiS: Rank position within their gender Age: Age of the participant during the race. Time: Official finish time of the participant. Pace: Average pace per mile during the race. Division: Age and gender category of the participant (e.g., M0119 = Male, ages 0-19). Hometown: Participant’s hometown (some entries are missing). Year: Year in which the race took place. Gender: Gender of the participant (M = Male, W = Female).

Data Collection and Challenges

This dataset was collected by scraping results from the Cherry Blossom Race website. While the client provided some guidance, the scraping process was a difficult process as the website was not designed for easy data extraction. The data was collected in multiple files, each covering a different time period, and required extensive cleaning and preprocessing to make it suitable for analysis. The data was then combined into a single dataframe for further analysis.

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

After collecting the data, the following steps were taken to clean and prepare it for analysis:

Handling Missing Values: We had a lot of columns with missing values, we had to decide whether to drop them or fill them with a value. Changing variable type: Columns such as Time and Pace were converted into numeric formats so they were easier to work with. Removing Outliers: Implausible race times or paces (e.g., unrealistically fast finish times) were identified and excluded. Removing Early Years: There were issues with the data in the first few years of the race, along with much smaller amounts of data, so we decided to remove the years 1973-1980.

# Step 1: Filter top 20 runners per year
top_runners <- Dat_Comb.weather %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  arrange(Minutes) %>%
  slice_head(n = 50) %>%
  ungroup()

# Step 2: Calculate average running time, temperature, and precipitation
avg_running_time <- top_runners %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(
    AvgTime = mean(Minutes, na.rm = TRUE),
    AvgTemp = mean(TMIN, na.rm = TRUE),
    AvgPrecip = mean(PRCP, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# Step 3: Detrend running time to account for overall improvement over the years
lm_trend <- lm(AvgTime ~ Year, data = avg_running_time)
avg_running_time <- avg_running_time %>%
  mutate(DetrendedTime = resid(lm_trend))
summary(lm_trend)

# Filter data for specific age groups and genders
filtered_data <- Dat_Comb.weather %>%
  filter(Age %in% c(25, 45), Gender %in% c("M", "W")) %>%
  mutate(
    Age_Group = paste(Gender, Age, sep = " ")
  )

# Summarize performance (e.g., average time in minutes) by year and age group
performance_by_age <- filtered_data %>%
  group_by(Year, Age_Group) %>%
  summarise(Average_Time = mean(Minutes, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

# Plot performance over age with smoothed lines
ggplot(performance_by_age, aes(x = Year, y = Average_Time, color = Age_Group)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = "loess", span=0.25,size = 1) +  # Add smoothed lines
  labs(
    title = "Performance Over The Years By Age",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Average Time (Minutes)",
    color = "Age"
  ) +
  theme_bw()
